WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:10.600
Hi, my name is Rika Gorn and I'm a Solutions Engineer at Posit.

00:00:10.600 --> 00:00:17.120
I help customers install and use Posit's pro products and help them solve complex architectural

00:00:17.120 --> 00:00:18.959
and infrastructure problems.

00:00:18.959 --> 00:00:25.120
I'm really excited to be teaching the first ever two-day DevOps for Data Scientists workshop

00:00:25.120 --> 00:00:28.799
at PositConf this September in Chicago.

00:00:28.799 --> 00:00:33.160
DevOps is the process by which the work of data scientists and developers, whether it's

00:00:33.160 --> 00:00:38.560
an R Markdown report, a Shiny app, or a model that serves predictions, can be shared and

00:00:38.560 --> 00:00:44.119
run across devices, across organizations, or even across countries.

00:00:44.119 --> 00:00:49.439
DevOps ensures that wherever your data products are, they are reliable, reproducible, performant,

00:00:49.439 --> 00:00:50.439
and secure.

00:00:50.439 --> 00:00:56.000
I want to share with you my three top reasons why you should join us at the DevOps workshop.

00:00:56.000 --> 00:01:00.639
First, you will learn the fundamentals of DevOps from the very beginning.

00:01:00.639 --> 00:01:06.199
If you don't know much about system administration or infrastructure as code, it's totally fine.

00:01:06.199 --> 00:01:08.480
This course will be made for you.

00:01:08.480 --> 00:01:12.040
The second reason why you should join is that we will be learning about DevOps from the

00:01:12.040 --> 00:01:14.160
lens of data science.

00:01:14.160 --> 00:01:19.480
You will learn how to move your code data science practices closer to the DevOps ideal

00:01:19.480 --> 00:01:24.559
using continuous integration and continuous deployment, how to write R code specifically

00:01:24.559 --> 00:01:30.760
for creating data-intensive applications, and how to use logs to monitor your app.

00:01:30.760 --> 00:01:35.400
The third reason why you should join the workshop is that you will leave with code deployed

00:01:35.400 --> 00:01:36.760
to the cloud.

00:01:36.760 --> 00:01:41.800
We will be running RStudio server in a Docker container and even be writing our own Docker

00:01:41.800 --> 00:01:42.800
files.

00:01:42.800 --> 00:01:47.680
I'm so excited to see everyone in September and hope to see you at the DevOps for Data

00:01:47.680 --> 00:01:48.680
Scientists workshop.

00:01:48.680 --> 00:01:48.680


